In this milestone you create the spike script, run it against the shared QuickPizza target, and write down when it started in UTC. Keep the live **Explore** or dashboard layout from the previous milestone visible while the test runs so you can relate the ramp to application metrics in real time. The next milestone is where you read thresholds, checks, and latency from the **Test Result** view and decide what those numbers mean for readiness.

When this path talks about anchoring the window, you record when the test started in UTC and reuse that same span of time in **Explore** for metrics, logs, and traces. Every signal then refers to the same spike as your k6 run, not unrelated traffic from another hour.

If `grafanacloud-k6` or metrics queries failed in the previous milestone, fix that in **Explore** before you run the spike so empty charts or access errors do not interrupt the lab.

To run the spike test in Grafana Cloud k6, complete the following steps.

1. Open **Testing & synthetics**, then **Performance**, then **Projects**.

1. Open the project where you run k6 tests (create one if you are prompted).

1. Click **Create new test**.

1. Under **Script editor**, select **Start scripting**.

   That opens the code editor instead of the Test Builder. If your stack opens the editor immediately after **Create new test**, skip this step. For the full flow, refer to [Use the script editor](/docs/grafana-cloud/testing/k6/author-run/script-editor/).

1. Replace the editor contents with the script that follows.

   The script ramps virtual users (VUs) quickly, holds load, then ramps down.

   Refer to [Spike testing](/docs/k6/latest/testing-guides/test-types/spike-testing/) for the general spike pattern. This milestone uses a shorter spike with a brief hold at peak so you can align metrics, logs, and traces in **Explore**.

   ```javascript
   import http from 'k6/http';
   import { check, sleep } from 'k6';

   export const options = {
     stages: [
       { duration: '30s', target: 5 },    // warm up
       { duration: '1m',  target: 100 }, // spike to 100 VUs
       { duration: '30s', target: 100 }, // hold the spike
       { duration: '1m',  target: 5 },   // recover
       { duration: '30s', target: 0 },   // ramp down
     ],
     // Lenient pass/fail so you can still complete the lab if the demo endpoint is slow; tighten in production scripts.
     thresholds: {
       http_req_duration: ['p(95)<15000'],
       checks: ['rate==1'],
     },
   };

   export default function () {
     const res = http.get('https://quickpizza.grafana.com');
     check(res, { 'status is 200': (r) => r.status === 200 });
     sleep(1);
   }
   ```

   If your organization blocks outbound calls, point `http.get` at the URL your administrators provide and keep the same `stages` so the spike shape matches the rest of the path.

   **Optional — your instrumented service only:** If k6 load-tests a service **you** run that already sends traces to Grafana Cloud Traces, add k6 tracing per [Correlate results with Grafana Cloud Traces](/docs/grafana-cloud/testing/k6/analyze-results/integration-with-grafana-cloud-traces/) (`instrumentHTTP` with the `w3c` propagator). Skip this for the shared QuickPizza URL in the script above.

1. Click **Run** (or your stack's equivalent).

   Wait until the test finishes before you write down UTC in the next step.

1. Write down the exact test start time in UTC.

   Every **Explore** step after you review this run uses a range that covers roughly five minutes before that time through fifteen minutes after the scheduled end (add buffer if your run queue delayed start). A single line in your notes is enough.

In the next milestone you interpret the **Test Result** view and capture the numbers your postmortem will need.
